<TR>
<TD></TD>

<TD><B><FONT FACE="Arial,Helvetica"><FONT SIZE=+1>Cell Phone Has A Place
on Boat, but VHF Is the Choice&nbsp;<BR>
in an Emergency, Columnist Writes</FONT></FONT></B></TD>

<TD></TD>
</TR>

<TR>
<TD></TD>

<TD><FONT FACE="Arial,Helvetica">As more boaters rely on cellular phones
for their communication needs, an informal pole shows that many Toldeo,
Ohio area boaters choose VHF in an emergency situation, columnist Shirley
Levy writes.&nbsp; VHF has greater range--up to 50 miles, compared to 10
to 15 miles for cellular--provides clear, uninterrupted service, facilitates
position tracking, and is the best way to reach the right people immediately.
(<A HREF="http://www.toledoblade.com/editorial/sports98/8h14sail.htm">TOLEDO
BLADE</A>)</FONT></TD>

<TD></TD>
</TR>

<TR>
<TD></TD>

<TD><BR></TD>

<TD></TD>
</TR>

<TR>
<TD></TD>

<TD><B><FONT FACE="Arial,Helvetica"><FONT SIZE=+1>Water Tower Cellular
Antennas Wanted</FONT></FONT></B></TD>

<TD></TD>
</TR>

<TR>
<TD></TD>

<TD><FONT FACE="Arial,Helvetica">Traverse City, Mich.-based MPI Wireless
has submitted a request to city officials asking for the permission to
erect a 10-foot tower atop a water tower in Alma, Mich. The antenna on
the water tower is less likely to cause problems--such as interference
with other communication devices or 911 radio signals--than building a
new tower altogether, according to some city officials. The issue will
be addressed at the Tuesday, Aug. 25 panel meeting. MPI has suggested paying
$6,600 a year and establishing a 10-year contract. (<A HREF="http://sa.mlive.com/news/tower.htm">MICHIGAN
LIVE</A>)</FONT></TD>

<TD></TD>
</TR>

<TR>
<TD></TD>

<TD><BR></TD>

<TD></TD>
